Introduction

This project was conducted as part of a nano degree at Udacity. Because data v isualization and data science is a passion, I decided to limit the time to invest in this project to 30 working hours. The data used in this project is called “Loan Data Form Prosper” and it was supplied with the project instructions. However, it is also available online (please see the references). In this project, I aimed at visualizing the different variable separately and against each other. The idea was to try to identify a pattern or a relationship between the different variables. I aimed to develop and test a model that helps to predict one of the important variables (from my point of view). Eventually, I was successful in developing a simple 5 variable model that predicts the yield on loans quite successfully.

I compared some indicators between the full df and the subdf. Ignoring possible outliers, it looks like that my sub-dataframe could represent the original dataframe. Among the numerical indicators I looked at: Term, BorrowerRate, ProsperRating (numeric), EmploymentStatusDuration, AvailableBankcardCredit, StatedMonthlyIncome, and LoanOriginalAmount.

Interesting to notice that some people with a monthly income of more than $250,000 are applying for loans with max $35000.

I will focus on some variables that I think they are of particular interest to the model I am trying to build:-

Some variables are reflecting each other (like ProsperRating (numeric), ProsperRating (Alpha) and ProsperScore). So I will choose one of them in such cases. Some variables are included in others (like LenderYield: The Lender yield is equal to the interest rate on the loan less the servicing fee). So I will use only the LenderYield and not the BorrowerRate. GroupKey includes if the borrower was in a group or not. Thus the variable CurrentlyInGroup could be omitted.

Univariate Analysis

I used the univariate analysis to understand the characteristics of Loan Borrowers.

The majority of the customers have low dept to income ratio (75% are below 0.32) and low Available Bank Card Credit (75% below $13,245). This is expected because the maximum loan in the data has the value of $35,000. With such small loans it is not expected that the majority of the customers are high earners.

75% of the loan applicants have monthly income below $6874. I believe the majority of the loan applicants are employees or small scale entrepreneurs.

Dept consolidation was the most frequent reason for applying for a loan. Business and home improvement were the 2nd and 3rd frequent loan reasons (respectively) in the data. Loan grades were not applicable for most of the loan borrowers (8943 out of 12000 in the subseted dataframe). However, most of the known grades were of the middle range (C-D).

As expected, most of the borrowers are employees. Their income could be verified. Owning a house or not was almost equally distributed among applicants.

It looks like only two credit grades are strongly influenced by the duration of employment. AA credit grade has higher employment status duration and grade HR has lower employment status duration.The rest of the grades are not showing a particular pattern.

It is more obvious that the increase in current credit lines is associated with higher credit grades.

Dept to income ratio is not playing a significant role in the credit grade. This might be expected in this case because the data is more about employees. Dept to income ratio might be more decisive in corporate loans. It is hard to verify Dept in the case of people (unless they volunteeringly reveal) .

Stated monthly income is playing a role in deciding the credit grade. To some extent, the boxes are moving up with the better credit grades.

It looks like the increase in Inquiries in the Last 6 Months is, to some extent, is associated with increase in the credit grade.

No risk no fun. As the credit grade decreases the lender yield increases

## 1 0.2231425 0.09134943 0.3549356

Multivariate Analysis

To some extent, better loan status is associated with lower monthly payment. The available Bank card credit does not affect the loan status. However, it does affect the yield on loans. It looks like credit grade increases with original loan amount. Loan original amount is to some extent discrete. Most of the loans are taking the value of $5000 and its duplicates (10K, 15K, 20K and so on).

Bad loans (with low loan status level) are generating higher lender yield. This could be due to penalties (for example) or higher interest rates.
For good loans (paid on schedule), the lender yield is associated with original loan amount.

A model for predicting the yield on loans was generated using five variables. The developed model can explain 26% of the variance. I tested many combinations including, for example, StatedMonthlyIncome. However, it did not enhance the R^2 of the model.

The model was tested using randomly selected ten samples. The model perfectly predicts the lender yield within the upper and the lower 95% confidence intervals.

Indeed, more investigation is needed to intensively evaluate the accuracy of the model and assess other model parameters.

Reflection

The developed model has an R square of 26% which is quite fair. However, when the model was tested using 10 random samples from the data, it was successful in predicting lender yield within the 95% confidence interval. This is quite impressing.

I limited the time to invest in this project to 30 working hours. If I had more time, I would continue in developing other models to predict other variables of interest.

There are many limitations for this model. First, the maximum loan value was only 35K. This model might work well with small personal loans. For corporate and large loans, more investigations must be conducted before reaching premature conclusions. Another limitation, I focussed only on a linear relationship. Probably exponential relationships exist in the data and revealing them might nhance the model accuracy.
